words: Hmm, when I was younger, I had a pretty bad stutter
and my own mom like had trouble understanding me.
So naturally um I wasn't, I didn't
feel inclined to talk to very many people as like the main sort of expression.
So um as I fell in love with dance, dance became my main
mode of expression. And uh it was there where I grew
um some of the strongest friendships that I ever had. And also
finding courage in, especially in like
stage fright. I used to have extremely bad stage fright, but you know with recitals
you can't really escape that. So, I don't know, it was just extremely positive
and I, I loved it so much. Um and
I got pretty good at it actually. I, we did it, the recital for The Nutcracker
and I was cast as Clara the main girl um who dances ballet
with the nutcracker. Um, so um
it was I, I didn't expect the news, but
one June um I remember my
uh dance instructor bringing us all together in a circle
and she was, uh, you know it felt,
it felt different. Like the meeting wasn't like any other meeting that we had. We didn't usually
have meetings, we just went into warm up and then straight to the barre to start our class.
And I remember her uh bringing us into a circle,
facing each other, and she broke the news that
uh she couldn't afford the increased
rent prices that the landlord was putting on the studio, so she had
to close, she had to close it down. And um, I remember that
was the hardest piece of news I had ever taken in my, in my life
that, at that point. Um, and when I,
I, I tried my like hardest to uh be strong
you know, but um I think I was twelve when this happened, so I'd been
in the Dance Network family for six years um, like half
my life at that point. So, um having that stripped away from me was
a huge loss and um
I, I couldn't keep the tears in.
And um I remember going back home and
for the nights, um following that news
I cried myself to sleep, cried when I woke up, uh
prayed to God that you know some miracle might happen and they would stay.
